This guide explains how to give AI coding agents current Trellis instructions
when they work in a service or browser app repository.

Use the raw files as stable, pasteable references:

- Short guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms.txt>
- Full guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms-full.txt>
- TypeScript guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms-typescript.txt>
- Svelte guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms-svelte.txt>
- Rust guide: <https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/llms-rust.txt>
- TypeScript AGENTS template: `/templates/trellis-service-typescript-AGENTS.md`
- Rust AGENTS template: `/templates/trellis-service-rust-AGENTS.md`
- Combined AGENTS template: `/templates/trellis-service-AGENTS.md`

## When to use each file

Use `llms.txt` as a small bootstrap document for every Trellis task. It points an
agent at the current service model, generated surfaces, and language-specific
guides.

Use `llms-full.txt` when the agent will change a contract, generated SDK usage,
service handlers, browser app wiring, operations, event publication, or
outbox/inbox code. It links to the language-specific TypeScript, Svelte, and Rust
guides.

For TypeScript SQL outbox work, point agents at `llms-typescript.txt` and ask
them to use `service.createSqlOutbox(...)` with closure over `deps.outbox`
instead of generating local outbox wrappers, manual `SqlOutboxRepository` handler
wiring, or per-handler Drizzle transaction adapters.

Use `llms-typescript.txt` for TypeScript service work and `llms-rust.txt` for
Rust service work. Most service repositories should link one of these rather than
asking agents to read both language stacks.

Use `llms-svelte.txt` for Svelte or SvelteKit browser apps that need
`createTrellisApp`, `TrellisProvider`, generated service SDK aliases for contract
`uses`, Vite aliases, or `svelte-check` path-map guidance. Svelte apps should use
`TrellisClientFor<typeof contract>` for their connected client type rather than
importing a generated app SDK.

Copy the TypeScript or Rust `templates/*-AGENTS.md` file into a service
repository as `AGENTS.md`, then fill in the local commands and paths. Keep local
rules in that file; keep Trellis-wide rules linked to the raw guides. The
combined template remains available for mixed-language repositories.

## Recommended setup for a service repo

1. Copy the matching template:

   ```sh
   curl -fsSL \
     https://raw.githubusercontent.com/qlever-llc/trellis/main/docs/static/templates/trellis-service-typescript-AGENTS.md \
     -o AGENTS.md
   ```

2. Fill in the repository-specific contract path, generation command, format
   command, typecheck command, test command, run command, and migration command.
3. Link the raw `llms.txt`, `llms-full.txt`, the relevant language-specific
   guide URL, and the matching AGENTS template from any other AI-facing project
   instructions.
4. Ask agents to read the short guide for all Trellis tasks, the full guide for
   contract or runtime-surface changes, and the relevant language guide before
   editing service or browser app code.

## What to ask agents to verify

Ask agents to run the service repo's own format, typecheck, lint, test, run, and
migration commands. If contracts changed, ask them to run `deno task prepare` for
TypeScript services or `cargo xtask prepare` for Rust services and verify
generated artifacts are updated from the source contract.
